[
  {
    "ch": "1",
    "title": "Nouns and Articles",
    "subCh1": "Nouns and Articles",
    "lessonContent": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "All nouns in Spanish are either masculine or feminine."
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "masculine nouns",
        "label2": "feminine nouns",
        "words1": ["el niño", "el libro", "la niña", "la playa"],
        "words2": ["the boy", "the book", "the girl", "the beach"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Nouns that ends in '-o' are masculine as well those ending in '-or', '-ema', '-ista', while those ending in '-a' , '-ion', '-ad', '-ud' are feminine.The plural of the nouns can be done by adding '-s' (if the noun ends in a vowel) and add '-es' (if the noun ends in a consonant)."
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["niño", "playa", "coche", "bar", "ciudad"],
        "words2": ["niños", "playas", "coches", "bares", "ciudades"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "There are few irregular plurals and nouns that do not change in the plural. Some nouns lose their written accents in the plural for reasons which follow the normal rules of pronunciation."
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["acciones", "jardine"],
        "words2": ["acciones", "jardines"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The noun carácter (character) changes its spoken stress in the plural and therefore loses its written accent: caracteres."
      }
    ],

    "subCh2": "Articles",
    "lessonContentSubCh2": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "There are two types of articles: definite and indefinite"
      },
      {
        "type": "subchapter",
        "text": "The definite article"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The equivalent of English 'the' has four forms in Spanish: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "Masculine Singular/Plural",
        "label2": "Feminine Singular/Plural",
        "words1": ["el", "la"],
        "words2": ["los", "las"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Note: Feminine nouns beginnings with a stressed 'a' or 'ha' are preceded by el and not la, but this does not make them masculine nouns, it is for ease of pronunciation."
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["el agua", "el hacha", "el águila"],
        "words2": ["la grand águila", "las hachas"]
      },
      {
        "type": "subchapter",
        "text": "The indefinite article"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The equivalents of English 'a', 'an' and, in the plural 'some', are: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "Masculine Singular/Plural",
        "label2": "Feminine Singular/Plural",
        "words1": ["un", "unos"],
        "words2": ["una", "unas"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "What has been said with regard to feminine nouns beginning in stressed a or ha is also true for the indefinite article:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["un hacha", "unas hachas"],
        "words2": ["un águila", "unas águilas"]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The plural forms ' unos ' and ' unas ' are commonly ommited without any significant change of meaning. When used, they often have the meaning of 'a few' or 'some'."
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["Hay galletas en la caja.", "Hay unos niños en la calle"],
        "words2": [
          "There are biscuits in the box. ",
          "There are some children in the street. "
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "'Uno' and 'una' are also used to mean 'one'."
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["Sólo tengo un hermano."],
        "words2": ["I only have one brother."]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "But note that the form uno/una is used to mean 'one' when referring to a masculine singular noun when the noun itself is not mentioned:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": [
          "¿Tienes un perro?",
          "Si, tengo uno.",
          "¿Tienes una casa?",
          "Si, tengo una."
        ],
        "words2": [
          "Do you have a dog? ",
          "Yes, I have one.",
          "Do you have a house? ",
          "Yes, I have one."
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "When referring to nouns in general: Nouns that refer to all the members of the relevant class usually require the use of the  definite article, although in English the article is omitted in such cases: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": [
          "Me gusta el café.",
          "La violencia es inaceptable.",
          "El ruido me molesta."
        ],
        "words2": [
          "I like coffee - i.e. all coffee in general.",
          "Violence is unacceptable - i.e. all violence. ",
          "Noise irritates me - i.e. all noise in general. "
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "With nouns in apposition: When the noun refers back to the one just mentioned, the definite article is omitted:"
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": ["Juan Carlos, rey de España", "Madrid, capital de España"],
        "words2": [
          "Juan Carlos, the King of Spain",
          "Madrid, the capital of Spain"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Before professions and status: Nouns that refer to professions, occupations and status, do not normally require an indefinite article, unless they are qualified by an adjective or other expression: "
      },
      {
        "type": "wordSection",
        "label1": "",
        "label2": "",
        "words1": [
          "Es médico.",
          "Es un buen médico.",
          "Soy soltero.",
          "Soy un soltero muy feliz."
        ],
        "words2": [
          "He's a doctor. ",
          "He's a good doctor. ",
          "I'm a bachelor.",
          "I'm a very happy bachelor."
        ]
      }
    ],

